THE MAP EDITOR
--------------

	INTRODUCTION

		The Map Editor is where blocks are arranged together in grids to form maps.
When a map is being edited, it is refered to as a project. You can have as many
projects open as you like, the only real restriction being that they will all
share a global palette and set of blocks.





	MAP EDITOR WINDOWS

		PROJECT WINDOW
			A project is viewed and edited through its project window(s). Because a map
can be just about any size at all, usually only a section of it is displayed
at a time. You can use the cursor keys or the scroll bars in the window border
to move the view to other areas of the map. Normally, the cursor keys will scroll
the map a single block in the specified direction, but traversing large maps in
this manner can be seriously tedious. To scroll more than one block at a time,
there are a number of keyboard modifier keys you can hold down whilst using the
cursor keys. ALT will cause scrolling to jump four blocks at a time. SHIFT causes
the view to jump a window at a time - for example, if you scroll right with SHIFT
held down, the left edge of the window will now be displaying the line of blocks
that used to lie along the right edge. The CTRL key is used to jump to the
extreme edges of the map.
			A project can have any number of project windows viewing it. When you make
a change in one project window, any other windows which were viewing the same
area of map will be automatically updated. A project must always have at least
one project window viewing it, so when the last project window is closed, the
project itself is discarded. Of course, if any unsaved work has been done on the
project, a requester is brought up to give you a way out.

			The title bar of a project window displays the name of the project you are
editing. If unsaved changes have been made to the project, a plus sign ('+') will
appear to the right of the name. If background fixing is switched on for the
project, a capital 'B' will also appear in the title bar.



